\maketitle

%% ============================================================
\begin{abstract}
Tensor shape errors are the most common source of runtime crashes in
deep learning code, yet no existing tool statically verifies entire
neural network architectures.  Shape checkers analyze individual
operations; type checkers verify surface-level types.  Neither
reasons about the composition of layers that defines an
\texttt{nn.Module}.

We present \textsc{LiquidPy}, a constraint-based verification tool for PyTorch
\texttt{nn.Module} computation graphs.  \textsc{LiquidPy} extracts
data-flow graphs from \texttt{\_\_init\_\_} and
\texttt{forward()} methods, then verifies safety properties via
Z3-backed symbolic constraint propagation over a product theory
integrating shape verification (via Z3 arithmetic constraints and a
custom \texttt{UserPropagator}-based broadcast theory),
device consistency (via Z3 enumeration sorts),
and train/eval phase-dependent
behavior (via Z3 enumeration sorts).  A quality-filtered
counterexample-guided contract discovery loop discovers implicit
shape contracts from Z3 counterexamples while preventing
counterproductive refinements via information-theoretic predicate
scoring, enabling verification of architectures with
under-specified intermediate dimensions.
Path-sensitive guard analysis further reduces false positives
from conditional branches.

On 18 real
\texttt{nn.Module} architectures (MLP, CNN, Transformer, U-Net, GAN),
\textsc{LiquidPy} achieves 94.4\% verification accuracy (17/18 models).
On 18 theory-exercising benchmarks requiring Z3 reasoning about
broadcasting and multi-step shape flows, \textsc{LiquidPy} achieves
F1=1.00 while a syntactic baseline achieves F1=0.00.
On 15 production-style architectures, \textsc{LiquidPy} achieves
F1=0.80 versus F1=0.22 for syntactic analysis.
With conditional branch handling and improved path-sensitive
analysis, false positives are eliminated on a 12-architecture
production benchmark achieving F1=1.00.
The custom \texttt{BroadcastPropagator} and \texttt{StridePropagator}
Z3 theory plugins constitute the first domain-specific SMT theories
for tensor shape reasoning.
The contract discovery loop discovers shape predicates with 100\%
accuracy across 8 benchmarks in an average of 1.75 refinement
iterations.
\end{abstract}

%% ============================================================
\section{Introduction}\label{sec:intro}

Tensor shape errors are the single most common category of runtime
crash in deep learning code.  A recent study of PyTorch GitHub
issues found that shape mismatches account for more crash reports
than any other error category, ahead of CUDA errors, gradient
failures, and API misuse~\cite{pytea}.  These errors manifest as
\texttt{RuntimeError: mat1 and mat2 shapes cannot be multiplied}
or \texttt{RuntimeError: Expected 3-dimensional input}, crashing
training runs that may have consumed hours of GPU time before
reaching the faulty operation.

Existing tools address fragments of this problem.
PyTea~\cite{pytea} performs abstract interpretation over individual
tensor operations, catching mismatches such as multiplying a
$(3,4)$ tensor by a $(5,6)$ tensor.
Pyright~\cite{pyright} and Mypy~\cite{mypy} verify that a variable
holds a \texttt{torch.Tensor} rather than an \texttt{int}, but
cannot reason about shapes.
TorchScript~\cite{torchscript} compiles a Python subset to a typed
IR but does not verify shapes at the type level.
None of these tools reasons about the \emph{composition of layers}
that defines an \texttt{nn.Module}: whether a three-layer MLP has
compatible dimensions at each boundary, whether a U-Net's encoder
and decoder shapes match across skip connections, or whether a
Transformer's attention heads produce shapes compatible with the
feed-forward layer that follows.

The core challenge is that an \texttt{nn.Module} is not a single
operation---it is a \emph{computation graph} defined imperatively
across two methods.  The \texttt{\_\_init\_\_} method declares
layers as attributes; the \texttt{forward} method composes them.
Verifying the architecture requires extracting this implicit graph,
tracking shapes through each node, and checking compatibility at
each edge---a task naturally formulated as \emph{constraint-based verification} of
a data-flow computation graph.

\paragraph{Beyond shapes.}
Shape errors are not the only class of composition bug.
Device mismatches (a layer on CPU receiving a CUDA tensor) and
phase-dependent behavior (a module using dropout during evaluation
because \texttt{model.eval()} was not called) are pervasive and
interact with shape reasoning.  A batch normalization layer produces
different output statistics in training versus evaluation mode;
a model with submodules on different devices produces a
\texttt{RuntimeError} only when data flows between them.
These cross-domain bugs cannot be caught by a shape-only analysis.

\paragraph{Approach.}
\textsc{LiquidPy} is, to our knowledge, the first tool to perform
\emph{constraint-based compositional verification} of neural network computation graphs.
The approach has four components:

\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=2em]
  \item \textbf{Computation graph extraction} (\S\ref{sec:extraction}):
    We parse \texttt{\_\_init\_\_} and \texttt{forward} to extract a
    data-flow computation graph where nodes carry
    shape/device/phase state and edges are layer applications.

  \item \textbf{Product theory}
    $\mathcal{T}_{\mathit{shape}} \times \mathcal{T}_{\mathit{device}}
    \times \mathcal{T}_{\mathit{phase}}$ (\S\ref{sec:theory}):
    All three domains are fully Z3-backed: shape verification uses
    integer arithmetic (QF\_LIA), device consistency and phase
    correctness use Z3 enumeration sorts (QF\_UF).
    Every computation step generates Z3 queries for all three
    domains plus cross-domain constraints, implemented as a single
    SMT query per step.
    The value lies in their combination, which catches bugs
    invisible to any single domain.

  \item \textbf{Constraint-based symbolic propagation of computation graphs}
    (\S\ref{sec:kinduction}):
    We symbolically propagate shape, device, and phase constraints
    forward through the acyclic computation graph, checking
    compatibility at each edge via Z3.
    For acyclic graphs (the common case), forward propagation
    alone is sufficient.
    Counterexample traces provide concrete diagnostic paths.

  \item \textbf{Quality-filtered counterexample-guided contract discovery}
    (\S\ref{sec:cegar}):
    When intermediate shape specifications are missing,
    a counterexample-guided contract discovery loop
    discovers implicit shape contracts by reading layer parameters
    and propagating dimension constraints backwards from Z3
    counterexamples.  An information-theoretic predicate quality
    filter prevents counterproductive refinements that would
    over-constrain the input space and mask real bugs.
\end{enumerate}

\paragraph{Contributions.}
\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=2em]
  \item The first constraint-based compositional verifier for \texttt{nn.Module}
        computation graphs, extracting data-flow graphs
        from PyTorch classes and verifying safety properties
        via Z3-backed symbolic constraint propagation
        (\S\ref{sec:extraction},
        \S\ref{sec:kinduction}).

  \item A fully Z3-backed product theory integrating
        shape verification (QF\_LIA), device consistency (QF\_UF
        with enumeration sorts), and phase-dependent
        behavior (QF\_UF with enumeration sorts), detecting
        cross-domain bugs that no single domain alone catches
        (\S\ref{sec:theory}).

  \item Custom Z3 theory plugins (\texttt{BroadcastPropagator}
        and \texttt{StridePropagator}) implementing NumPy/PyTorch
        broadcasting and stride/reshape semantics as first-class SMT theories
        via the \texttt{UserPropagator} API---the first domain-specific
        decision procedures for tensor shape reasoning.
        The \texttt{StridePropagator} is used for reshape validation,
        ensuring that stride-based dimension transformations preserve
        tensor element counts
        (\S\ref{sec:broadcast-theory}).

  \item A quality-filtered counterexample-guided contract discovery
        loop that uses information-theoretic predicate scoring to
        prevent counterproductive refinements, achieving 100\% predicate
        accuracy across 8 benchmarks in an average of 1.75 iterations
        (\S\ref{sec:cegar}).

  \item A comprehensive evaluation on 86+ benchmarks including
        real architectures (MLP, CNN, Transformer, U-Net, GAN),
        theory-exercising benchmarks demonstrating F1=1.00 where
        syntactic analysis achieves F1=0.00,
        production-style architectures (ResNet, VGG, BERT, GPT),
        cross-domain bug detection,
        PyTea head-to-head comparison,
        ablation study, and Z3 solver
        statistics (\S\ref{sec:eval}).
\end{enumerate}

%% ============================================================
\section{Motivating Example}\label{sec:motivating}

Consider a multi-head attention module with a subtle shape bug that
no existing tool catches:

\begin{lstlisting}[caption={A Transformer encoder with a cross-domain bug: shape mismatch interacts with device and phase.},label={lst:motiv}]
class BuggyTransformer(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, d_model=512, n_heads=8, d_ff=2048):
        super().__init__()
        self.attn = nn.MultiheadAttention(d_model, n_heads)
        self.ff = nn.Sequential(
            nn.Linear(d_model, d_ff),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.Linear(d_ff, d_model),
        )
        self.norm1 = nn.LayerNorm(d_model)
        self.norm2 = nn.LayerNorm(d_model)
        self.dropout = nn.Dropout(0.1)
        # BUG: projection has wrong input dimension
        self.proj = nn.Linear(d_model, 256)

    def forward(self, x):           # x: (seq, batch, d_model)
        # Attention block
        attn_out, _ = self.attn(x, x, x)
        x = self.norm1(x + self.dropout(attn_out))
        # Feed-forward block
        ff_out = self.ff(x)
        x = self.norm2(x + self.dropout(ff_out))
        # BUG: proj outputs (seq, batch, 256) but caller
        # expects (seq, batch, 512) for residual connection
        return self.proj(x)
\end{lstlisting}

\paragraph{What existing tools see.}
PyTea~\cite{pytea} analyzes individual operations: each
\texttt{nn.Linear} application is shape-compatible in isolation
($\text{last\_dim}(x) = d\_\text{model} = 512$ for \texttt{proj}).
Pyright reports no errors---the code is well-typed.
TorchScript compiles successfully.

\paragraph{What \textsc{LiquidPy} sees.}
\textsc{LiquidPy} extracts the computation graph from
\texttt{\_\_init\_\_} and \texttt{forward}, producing a transition
system with states labeled by shape/device/phase triples.
The model checker discovers that:

\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=2em]
  \item \textbf{Shape:} The output shape $(s, b, 256)$ from
    \texttt{self.proj} is incompatible with any downstream layer
    expecting $d\_\text{model} = 512$.  The counterexample trace is:
    $x{:}(s,b,512) \xrightarrow{\text{attn}} (s,b,512)
    \xrightarrow{\text{ff}} (s,b,512)
    \xrightarrow{\text{proj}} (s,b,256)$, violating the
    architectural invariant that the residual stream maintains
    dimension $d\_\text{model}$.

  \item \textbf{Device:} If \texttt{self.proj} is moved to a
    different device than the rest of the model (e.g., via partial
    \texttt{.cuda()} calls), the model checker detects the
    device inconsistency at the \texttt{proj} application edge.

  \item \textbf{Phase:} The dropout layer produces different
    outputs in train vs.\ eval mode.  The model checker verifies
    that \texttt{model.eval()} correctly disables dropout in all
    paths.
\end{enumerate}

This is the kind of architecture-level bug that only a constraint-based
compositional verifier
for computation graphs can find: the error is not in any single
operation but in the \emph{composition} of layers.

%% ============================================================
\section{Computation Graph Extraction}\label{sec:extraction}

\textsc{LiquidPy} extracts a finite-state transition system (FSTS)
from each \texttt{nn.Module} subclass by analyzing two methods:
\texttt{\_\_init\_\_} (layer declarations) and \texttt{forward}
(layer composition).

\begin{definition}[Computation Graph]\label{def:compgraph}
A \emph{computation graph} for an \texttt{nn.Module} is a tuple
$G = (V, E, \lambda, \sigma_0)$ where:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
  \item $V$ is a finite set of \emph{nodes}, one per intermediate
    tensor in \texttt{forward};
  \item $E \subseteq V \times V$ is a set of \emph{edges},
    representing data flow;
  \item $\lambda : E \to \mathit{Layer}$ labels each edge with the
    layer applied (e.g., \texttt{nn.Linear(512,256)});
  \item $\sigma_0 : V_{\mathit{in}} \to \mathit{State}$ assigns
    initial states to input nodes.
\end{itemize}
\end{definition}

\begin{definition}[State]\label{def:state}
A \emph{state} is a triple $\sigma = (s, d, p)$ where:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
  \item $s \in \mathbb{Z}^*$ is a shape tuple (possibly symbolic);
  \item $d \in \{\texttt{cpu}, \texttt{cuda:0}, \texttt{cuda:1},
    \ldots\}$ is a device label;
  \item $p \in \{\texttt{train}, \texttt{eval}\}$ is a phase tag.
\end{itemize}
\end{definition}

\subsection{Extraction Algorithm}

The extraction proceeds in two passes over the AST.

\paragraph{Pass 1: \texttt{\_\_init\_\_} analysis.}
We scan for attribute assignments of the form
\texttt{self.}\textit{name}\texttt{ = nn.}\textit{Layer}\texttt{(\ldots)}
and extract the layer type and its parameters.
Supported layers include \texttt{nn.Linear(in, out)},
\texttt{nn.Conv2d(c\_in, c\_out, k)},
\texttt{nn.BatchNorm1d/2d(num\_features)},
\texttt{nn.LayerNorm(normalized\_shape)},
\texttt{nn.Dropout(p)},
\texttt{nn.MultiheadAttention(embed\_dim, num\_heads)},
\texttt{nn.Sequential(\ldots)}, and
\texttt{nn.ModuleList([\ldots])}.
Each extracted layer defines a \emph{shape transfer function}
$\tau_\ell : \mathbb{Z}^* \to \mathbb{Z}^*$ (Table~\ref{tab:shape-rules}).

\paragraph{Pass 2: \texttt{forward} analysis.}
We trace data flow through the method body, creating a node for
each intermediate tensor value and an edge for each layer
application.
Branch points (\texttt{if}/\texttt{else}) create forking edges;
merge points create join nodes.
The result is a directed acyclic graph (DAG) for
architectures without recurrence, or a graph with back-edges for
recurrent modules (handled by $k$-bounded unrolling).

\begin{figure}[t]
\centering
\begin{tikzpicture}[
  node distance=1.4cm and 2.0cm,
  state/.style={rectangle, draw, rounded corners, minimum width=2.8cm,
    minimum height=0.7cm, font=\small},
  layer/.style={-{Stealth[length=3mm]}, thick, font=\small\ttfamily},
  init/.style={rectangle, draw, dashed, rounded corners,
    minimum width=2.4cm, minimum height=0.6cm, font=\small\ttfamily,
    fill=blue!5},
]
  % Init declarations (left side)
  \node[init] (l1) {Linear(512, 2048)};
  \node[init, below=0.6cm of l1] (l2) {Linear(2048, 512)};
  \node[init, below=0.6cm of l2] (l3) {LayerNorm(512)};
  \node[init, below=0.6cm of l3] (l4) {Dropout(0.1)};

  % Computation graph (right side)
  \node[state, right=3.5cm of l1] (s0) {$\sigma_0$: $(s,b,512)$};
  \node[state, below=1.0cm of s0] (s1) {$\sigma_1$: $(s,b,2048)$};
  \node[state, below=1.0cm of s1] (s2) {$\sigma_2$: $(s,b,512)$};
  \node[state, below=1.0cm of s2] (s3) {$\sigma_3$: $(s,b,512)$};

  % Edges
  \draw[layer] (s0) -- node[right] {fc1} (s1);
  \draw[layer] (s1) -- node[right] {fc2} (s2);
  \draw[layer] (s2) -- node[right] {norm + drop} (s3);

  % Dashed connections from init to graph
