\subsection{Shape Transfer Functions}

Each layer type defines a shape transfer function.
Table~\ref{tab:shape-rules} summarizes the supported operations.

\begin{table}[t]
\centering
\caption{Shape transfer functions for tensor operations.  $s_x$
  denotes the input shape.}
\label{tab:shape-rules}
\small
\begin{tabular}{@{}lll@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Operation} & \textbf{Precondition} & \textbf{Result shape} \\
\midrule
\texttt{A @ B}
  & $\mathit{cols}(A) = \mathit{rows}(B)$
  & $(\ldots, \mathit{rows}(A), \mathit{cols}(B))$ \\[3pt]
\texttt{A + B} (broadcast)
  & $\forall i.\; s_A[i]{=}s_B[i] \lor s_A[i]{=}1 \lor s_B[i]{=}1$
  & $(\max(s_A[i], s_B[i]))_i$ \\[3pt]
\texttt{torch.cat([A,B], dim=d)}
  & $\forall i \neq d.\; s_A[i] = s_B[i]$
  & $s_A[d{:=}s_A[d]+s_B[d]]$ \\[3pt]
\texttt{nn.Linear(m,n)(x)}
  & $\mathit{last\_dim}(x) = m$
  & $s_x[\text{-}1{:=}n]$ \\[3pt]
\texttt{nn.Conv2d(c\_in,c\_out,k)(x)}
  & $s_x[1] = c\_\mathit{in}$
  & $(s_x[0], c\_\mathit{out}, H', W')$ \\[3pt]
\texttt{x.reshape(s)}
  & $\prod s_x[i] = \prod s[j]$
  & $s$ \\[3pt]
\texttt{x.transpose(i,j)}
  & $i, j < \mathit{ndim}(x)$
  & $s_x[\text{swap}(i,j)]$ \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

Auxiliary projections used throughout:
\begin{align*}
  \mathit{ndim}(v) &= |\mathit{shape}(v)|, \quad
  \mathit{rows}(v) = \mathit{shape}(v)[\mathit{ndim}(v){-}2], \quad
  \mathit{cols}(v) = \mathit{shape}(v)[\mathit{ndim}(v){-}1]
\end{align*}

%% ============================================================
\section{Product Theory}\label{sec:theory}

We formalize the verification domain as a product of three
first-order theories, each decidable, whose combination is also
decidable by the Nelson--Oppen method~\cite{nelsonoppen}.

\subsection{Theory of Shapes $\mathcal{T}_{\mathit{shape}}$}

\begin{definition}[Shape Theory]
$\mathcal{T}_{\mathit{shape}}$ is a many-sorted first-order theory
with:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
  \item \textbf{Sorts:} $\mathit{Dim}$ (integers $\geq 1$),
    $\mathit{Shape}$ (finite tuples over $\mathit{Dim}$),
    $\mathit{Idx}$ (natural numbers).
  \item \textbf{Functions:}
    $\mathit{get} : \mathit{Shape} \times \mathit{Idx} \to \mathit{Dim}$,
    $\mathit{len} : \mathit{Shape} \to \mathit{Idx}$,
    $\mathit{set} : \mathit{Shape} \times \mathit{Idx} \times
    \mathit{Dim} \to \mathit{Shape}$,
    $\mathit{prod} : \mathit{Shape} \to \mathbb{Z}$.
  \item \textbf{Axioms:} Standard tuple axioms plus
    $\forall s.\;\forall i < \mathit{len}(s).\;
    \mathit{get}(s,i) \geq 1$.
\end{itemize}
\end{definition}

The quantifier-free fragment of $\mathcal{T}_{\mathit{shape}}$
(with concrete tuple lengths) is reducible to QF-LIA and hence
decidable.  When reshape is involved, the product constraint
$\prod s_x[i] = \prod s[j]$ introduces multiplication of
variables, placing the problem in QF-NIA; we handle this via
Z3's nonlinear arithmetic solver.

\subsection{Theory of Devices $\mathcal{T}_{\mathit{device}}$}

\begin{definition}[Device Theory]
$\mathcal{T}_{\mathit{device}}$ is an equality theory over a finite
sort $\mathit{Dev} = \{\texttt{cpu}, \texttt{cuda:0},
\texttt{cuda:1}, \ldots\}$ with:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
  \item \textbf{Function:}
    $\mathit{dev} : \mathit{Tensor} \to \mathit{Dev}$.
  \item \textbf{Axioms:}
    (1)~Layer application preserves device:
    $\mathit{dev}(\ell(x)) = \mathit{dev}(x)$ when $\ell$ is a
    stateless operation.
    (2)~Stateful layers inherit their registered device:
    $\mathit{dev}(\ell(x)) = \mathit{dev}(\ell)$ for layers
    $\ell$ with parameters.
    (3)~Binary operations require device agreement:
    $\mathit{dev}(x \oplus y) = \mathit{dev}(x) = \mathit{dev}(y)$.
\end{itemize}
\end{definition}

$\mathcal{T}_{\mathit{device}}$ is implemented in Z3 using
\emph{enumeration sorts}: device variables are Z3 constants over
an enumeration sort, and device consistency constraints are Z3
equalities.  This gives us full SMT-backed reasoning for device
consistency, integrated into the same Z3 context as shape
constraints.  The theory falls within QF\_UF (quantifier-free
uninterpreted functions with equality).

\subsection{Theory of Phases $\mathcal{T}_{\mathit{phase}}$}

\begin{definition}[Phase Theory]
$\mathcal{T}_{\mathit{phase}}$ is a two-valued theory with sort
$\mathit{Phase} = \{\texttt{train}, \texttt{eval}\}$ and:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
  \item \textbf{Function:}
    $\mathit{phase} : \mathit{Module} \to \mathit{Phase}$.
  \item \textbf{Axioms:}
    (1)~\texttt{model.train()} sets
    $\mathit{phase}(m) = \texttt{train}$ for $m$ and all
    submodules.
    (2)~\texttt{model.eval()} sets
    $\mathit{phase}(m) = \texttt{eval}$ for $m$ and all
    submodules.
    (3)~Phase-dependent layers:
    $\mathit{phase}(m) = \texttt{eval} \Rightarrow
    \mathit{dropout\_active}(m) = \mathit{false}$.
\end{itemize}
\end{definition}

$\mathcal{T}_{\mathit{phase}}$ is implemented in Z3 using
enumeration sorts, analogous to $\mathcal{T}_{\mathit{device}}$.
Phase variables are Z3 constants over an enumeration sort
$\{\texttt{train}, \texttt{eval}\}$, and phase constraints are
Z3 equalities within the same SMT context.  This ensures that
phase reasoning participates in the same Z3 satisfiability check
as shape and device constraints.

\subsection{Product Theory and Cross-Sort Axioms}

\begin{definition}[Product Theory]\label{def:product}
The product theory is
$\mathcal{T}_\Pi = \mathcal{T}_{\mathit{shape}} \times
\mathcal{T}_{\mathit{device}} \times \mathcal{T}_{\mathit{phase}}$
with cross-sort axioms:
\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=2em]
  \item \textbf{Device--shape interaction:}
    $\mathit{dev}(x) \neq \mathit{dev}(y) \Rightarrow
    (x \oplus y)$ is undefined (error state).
  \item \textbf{Phase--shape interaction:}
    $\mathit{phase}(m) = \texttt{train} \wedge
    \mathit{has\_batchnorm}(m) \Rightarrow$
    output shape depends on running statistics.
  \item \textbf{Phase--device interaction:}
    $\mathit{phase}(m) = \texttt{eval} \wedge
    \mathit{has\_dropout}(m) \Rightarrow$
    dropout is identity (no shape change, but semantic change).
\end{enumerate}
\end{definition}

\begin{figure}[t]
\centering
\begin{tikzpicture}[
  theory/.style={ellipse, draw, thick, minimum width=3cm,
    minimum height=1.5cm, font=\small\bfseries, align=center},
  axiom/.style={font=\small\itshape, align=center},
  arr/.style={<->, thick, dashed}
]
  \node[theory, fill=blue!10] (shape) at (0, 0)
    {$\mathcal{T}_{\mathit{shape}}$\\Dim, Shape\\matmul, broadcast};
  \node[theory, fill=red!10] (device) at (5.5, 0)
    {$\mathcal{T}_{\mathit{device}}$\\Dev\\equality};
  \node[theory, fill=green!10] (phase) at (2.75, -3.2)
    {$\mathcal{T}_{\mathit{phase}}$\\Phase\\train/eval};

  \draw[arr] (shape) -- node[above, axiom] {dev mismatch\\$\Rightarrow$ error}
    (device);
  \draw[arr] (shape) -- node[left, axiom, xshift=-5pt] {batchnorm\\stats}
    (phase);
  \draw[arr] (device) -- node[right, axiom, xshift=5pt] {dropout\\identity}
    (phase);

  % Product label
  \node[above=0.6cm of shape, xshift=2.75cm, font=\large\bfseries]
    {$\mathcal{T}_\Pi = \mathcal{T}_{\mathit{shape}} \times
     \mathcal{T}_{\mathit{device}} \times \mathcal{T}_{\mathit{phase}}$};
\end{tikzpicture}
\caption{The product theory $\mathcal{T}_\Pi$.  All three domains
  are fully Z3-backed: shape verification uses integer arithmetic
  (QF\_LIA); device and phase use enumeration sorts (QF\_UF).
  Every computation step generates a single SMT query covering
  all three domains.  Cross-domain axioms (dashed
  arrows) capture interactions: device mismatches produce errors,
  phase affects batchnorm statistics and dropout behavior.
  The value lies in the combination, not the individual theories.}
\label{fig:product}
\end{figure}

\begin{theorem}[Decidability of $\mathcal{T}_\Pi$]\label{thm:decidable}
The quantifier-free satisfiability problem for $\mathcal{T}_\Pi$
(with concrete tuple lengths) is decidable.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}[Proof sketch]
$\mathcal{T}_{\mathit{shape}}$ (QF-LIA with concrete lengths),
$\mathcal{T}_{\mathit{device}}$ (equality over finite domain), and
$\mathcal{T}_{\mathit{phase}}$ (two-element Boolean) are each
decidable.  Note that $\mathcal{T}_{\mathit{device}}$ and
$\mathcal{T}_{\mathit{phase}}$ have finite sorts and are therefore
\emph{not} stably infinite, so the classical Nelson--Oppen
combination theorem~\cite{nelsonoppen} does not directly apply.
Instead, decidability of the combination follows from the
Tinelli--Zarba extension~\cite{tinelli03} for combining theories
with finite sorts, or more directly, from the fact that Z3's
built-in theory combination handles these finite domains natively.
The cross-sort axioms introduce only equality
constraints between sorts.
Full proof in Appendix~\ref{app:decidability}.
\end{proof}

\begin{proposition}[Complexity of $\mathcal{T}_\Pi$]\label{prop:complexity}
QF satisfiability of $\mathcal{T}_\Pi$ is:
\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=2em]
  \item In P when all dimensions are concrete and no reshape is
    involved (each shape constraint is a conjunction of integer
    equalities).
  \item NP-hard when reshape is involved with symbolic dimensions
    (by reduction from PARTITION: given multiset $S$, can we
    partition the dimensions into two groups with equal product?).
  \item Decidable in constant time for $\mathcal{T}_{\mathit{device}}$
    and $\mathcal{T}_{\mathit{phase}}$
    in isolation (Z3 enumeration sort equality and two-element
    enumeration sort, respectively).
\end{enumerate}
\end{proposition}

%% ============================================================
\section{Domain-Specific SMT Theory for Broadcasting}\label{sec:broadcast-theory}

While broadcasting constraints can be encoded as QF-LIA formulas
(Table~\ref{tab:shape-rules}), this na\"ive encoding generates
large clause sets for high-rank tensors and does not exploit the
structure of broadcasting during search.  We instead implement
broadcasting as a \emph{first-class Z3 theory} via the
\texttt{UserPropagator} API, enabling eager propagation and
conflict clause generation within the DPLL(T) loop.

\subsection{The \texttt{UserPropagator} API}

Z3's \texttt{UserPropagator} allows a client to register a custom
theory that participates in the solver's search:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
  \item \textbf{\texttt{push}/\texttt{pop}:} Track the solver's
    backtracking stack.
  \item \textbf{\texttt{fixed}:} Called when the solver assigns a
    value to a registered variable.
  \item \textbf{\texttt{final}:} Called when the solver has a
    candidate model; the theory may accept or add conflicts.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Broadcast Propagation Rules}

We register dimension variables $d^A_i$, $d^B_i$, $d^{\mathit{out}}_i$
for each axis.  Algorithm~\ref{alg:broadcast} shows the propagation
logic.

\begin{algorithm}[t]
\caption{Broadcast theory propagation.}
\label{alg:broadcast}
\begin{algorithmic}[1]
\Procedure{Fixed}{var, value}
  \If{var is $d^A_i$ or $d^B_i$}
    \State $a \gets \mathrm{val}(d^A_i)$;\;
           $b \gets \mathrm{val}(d^B_i)$
    \If{$a \neq \bot$ \textbf{and} $b \neq \bot$}
      \If{$a = b$}
        \State \textbf{propagate} $d^{\mathit{out}}_i = a$
          \Comment{matching dims}
      \ElsIf{$a = 1$}
        \State \textbf{propagate} $d^{\mathit{out}}_i = b$
          \Comment{broadcast $A$}
      \ElsIf{$b = 1$}
        \State \textbf{propagate} $d^{\mathit{out}}_i = a$
          \Comment{broadcast $B$}
      \Else
        \State \textbf{conflict} $\{d^A_i{=}a,\; d^B_i{=}b\}$
          \Comment{incompatible}
      \EndIf
    \EndIf
  \EndIf
\EndProcedure
\end{algorithmic}
\end{algorithm}

\paragraph{Propagation.}
When Z3 assigns $d^A_i = 3$ and $d^B_i = 1$, the broadcast
theory eagerly propagates $d^{\mathit{out}}_i = 3$ as a theory
consequence, pruning the search space immediately.

\paragraph{Conflict generation.}
When Z3 assigns $d^A_i = 3$ and $d^B_i = 5$, the theory generates
the conflict clause $\neg(d^A_i{=}3 \wedge d^B_i{=}5)$, causing
Z3 to backtrack without exploring the subtree.

\paragraph{Stride theory plugin.}
We apply the same \texttt{UserPropagator} pattern to implement a
stride theory for convolution output dimensions.  The stride theory
propagates $H' = \lfloor(H + 2p - k)/s\rfloor + 1$ eagerly when
the input height, padding, kernel size, and stride are fixed,
avoiding the need for nonlinear arithmetic encoding.

%% ============================================================
\section{Constraint-Based Symbolic Propagation}\label{sec:kinduction}

Given a computation graph $G = (V, E, \lambda, \sigma_0)$ and a
safety property $\varphi$ (e.g., ``all intermediate shapes are
compatible''), we verify $\varphi$ by symbolically propagating
constraints forward through the graph and checking each edge
with Z3.

Since \texttt{nn.Module.forward()} defines an acyclic directed
computation graph (a DAG), verification reduces to bounded
symbolic execution: we propagate shape, device, and phase
constraints along each path from input to output, checking
compatibility at every edge.  For acyclic graphs, this forward
pass alone is complete---no inductive argument is needed.

\paragraph{Remark.}
We frame our approach in terms of bounded model
checking~\cite{biere99} for uniformity with the verification
literature.  However, we note that on acyclic computation
graphs (which covers all feedforward architectures including
MLPs, CNNs, Transformers, U-Nets, and GANs), the ``base case''
of checking all paths up to depth $|V|$ is already exhaustive.
An inductive step in the style of $k$-induction~\cite{sheeran00}
would be needed only for recurrent architectures (RNNs, LSTMs)
with unbounded unrolling, which we handle via bounded
approximation and report results as ``verified up to $k$ steps.''

\begin{definition}[Safety Property]
A safety property $\varphi$ over $G$ is a formula in
$\mathcal{T}_\Pi$ that must hold at every reachable state:
\[
  \varphi(\sigma) \;\triangleq\;
  \varphi_{\mathit{shape}}(\sigma.s) \;\wedge\;
  \varphi_{\mathit{device}}(\sigma.d) \;\wedge\;
  \varphi_{\mathit{phase}}(\sigma.p)
\]
where $\varphi_{\mathit{shape}}$ asserts shape compatibility at
each edge, $\varphi_{\mathit{device}}$ asserts device consistency,
and $\varphi_{\mathit{phase}}$ asserts phase correctness.
\end{definition}

\subsection{Forward Symbolic Propagation}

The verification checks all computation paths through the DAG:
\[
  \mathit{Check} \;\triangleq\;
  \bigwedge_{i=0}^{|V|}
  \big( \sigma_0 \xrightarrow{e_1} \sigma_1 \xrightarrow{e_2}
  \cdots \xrightarrow{e_i} \sigma_i
  \;\Rightarrow\; \varphi(\sigma_i) \big)
\]
This is a constraint-based verification query: we propagate constraints
forward through the computation graph and ask Z3 whether any step
violates $\varphi$.
Since the computation graph is acyclic with $|V|$ nodes,
forward propagation covers all computation steps exhaustively.
(This formulation is equivalent to bounded model checking~\cite{biere99}
over the unrolled data-flow graph.)

\subsection{Inductive Step (Recurrent Architectures Only)}

For recurrent architectures (RNNs, LSTMs) with cycles, forward
propagation alone does not suffice.  In this case, we employ a
$k$-bounded inductive step that checks whether $\varphi$ holding for $k$
consecutive states implies it holds for the next:
\[
  \mathit{Step}(k) \;\triangleq\;
  \bigwedge_{i=0}^{k-1} \varphi(\sigma_i) \;\wedge\;
  \sigma_{k-1} \xrightarrow{e_k} \sigma_k
  \;\Rightarrow\; \varphi(\sigma_k)
\]

\begin{theorem}[$k$-Induction Soundness~\cite{sheeran00}]
If $\mathit{Check}$ and $\mathit{Step}(k)$ hold, then $\varphi$
holds at all reachable states of $G$.
\end{theorem}

\begin{theorem}[Soundness of Product-Theory Verification]\label{thm:soundness}
Let $G = (V, E, \lambda)$ be a computation graph with shape transfer functions $\tau_s$, device transfer functions $\tau_d$, and phase predicates $\tau_p$. If the constraint-based verifier with product theory $\mathcal{T}_\Pi = \mathcal{T}_{\mathit{shape}} \times \mathcal{T}_{\mathit{device}} \times \mathcal{T}_{\mathit{phase}}$ returns \textsc{Safe}, then for all concrete input assignments satisfying the discovered shape contracts, every computation step satisfies all safety properties.
\end{theorem}

\begin{proof}
By construction, the verifier encodes each computation step $e_i \in E$ as a conjunction of constraints in $\mathcal{T}_\Pi$. For each step $i$:
\begin{enumerate}
\item The shape constraint $\phi_s^i$ encodes $\tau_s(e_i)$ as Z3 arithmetic (QF\_LIA) with the broadcast theory propagator ensuring broadcasting semantics.
\item The device constraint $\phi_d^i$ encodes $\tau_d(e_i)$ as equality over the Device enumeration sort.
\item The phase constraint $\phi_p^i$ encodes $\tau_p(e_i)$ as equality over the Phase enumeration sort.
\end{enumerate}
The safety query asks Z3: $\exists \sigma.\ \bigwedge_{i} (\phi_s^i \wedge \phi_d^i \wedge \phi_p^i) \wedge \neg\textit{safe}$. If UNSAT, no assignment falsifies safety. The broadcast theory propagator (Section~\ref{sec:broadcast-theory}) is sound by construction: it raises conflicts only when concrete dimension assignments violate NumPy broadcasting rules, and propagates equalities only when they are implied by the broadcasting semantics. Theory combination is sound by the Tinelli--Zarba extension~\cite{tinelli03} of the Nelson--Oppen framework: $\mathcal{T}_{\mathit{shape}}$ operates over integer arithmetic (stably infinite), while $\mathcal{T}_{\mathit{device}}$ and $\mathcal{T}_{\mathit{phase}}$ are over finite enumeration sorts. The Tinelli--Zarba extension handles finite sorts by enumerating arrangements over them. The signatures are disjoint (shape uses $\{\mathit{get},\mathit{len},\mathit{set},\mathit{prod}\}$, device uses $\{\mathit{dev}\}$, phase uses $\{\mathit{phase}\}$) and cross-sort constraints introduce only shared equality variables, handled via explicit equality propagation.
\end{proof}

For the acyclic computation graphs that constitute all of our
feedforward benchmarks (MLPs, CNNs, Transformers, U-Nets, GANs),
the forward propagation check alone is sufficient and the
inductive step is vacuously satisfied.  The depth of the DAG
provides a natural bound: setting $k = |V|$ makes the check
exhaustive.  For recurrent architectures, we report results
as ``verified up to $k$ steps.''

\begin{figure}[t]
\centering
\begin{tikzpicture}[
  node distance=1.6cm,
  state/.style={circle, draw, thick, minimum size=0.9cm,
    font=\small},
  safe/.style={state, fill=green!15},
  unsafe/.style={state, fill=red!15},
  edge/.style={-{Stealth[length=2.5mm]}, thick},
]
  % Base case
  \node[font=\small\bfseries] at (0, 1.2) {Base case ($k=3$)};
  \node[safe] (b0) at (0, 0) {$\sigma_0$};
  \node[safe] (b1) at (1.6, 0) {$\sigma_1$};
  \node[safe] (b2) at (3.2, 0) {$\sigma_2$};
  \node[safe] (b3) at (4.8, 0) {$\sigma_3$};
  \draw[edge] (b0) -- node[above, font=\scriptsize] {$e_1$} (b1);
  \draw[edge] (b1) -- node[above, font=\scriptsize] {$e_2$} (b2);
  \draw[edge] (b2) -- node[above, font=\scriptsize] {$e_3$} (b3);
  \node[right=0.3cm of b3, font=\small, green!50!black] {$\checkmark\;\varphi$};

  % Inductive step
  \node[font=\small\bfseries] at (0, -1.8) {Inductive step};
  \node[safe] (i0) at (0, -3) {$\sigma_i$};
  \node[safe] (i1) at (1.6, -3) {$\sigma_{i{+}1}$};
  \node[safe] (i2) at (3.2, -3) {$\sigma_{i{+}2}$};
  \node[safe] (i3) at (4.8, -3) {$\sigma_{i{+}3}$};
  \draw[edge] (i0) -- (i1);
  \draw[edge] (i1) -- (i2);
  \draw[edge] (i2) -- (i3);
  \node[above=0.15cm of i0, font=\scriptsize] {$\varphi$};
  \node[above=0.15cm of i1, font=\scriptsize] {$\varphi$};
  \node[above=0.15cm of i2, font=\scriptsize] {$\varphi$};
  \node[right=0.3cm of i3, font=\small, green!50!black]
    {$\Rightarrow \varphi$};

  % Counterexample
  \node[font=\small\bfseries] at (0, -4.8) {Counterexample trace};
  \node[safe] (c0) at (0, -6) {$\sigma_0$};
  \node[safe] (c1) at (1.6, -6) {$\sigma_1$};
  \node[unsafe] (c2) at (3.2, -6) {$\sigma_2$};
  \draw[edge] (c0) -- node[above, font=\scriptsize] {$e_1$} (c1);
  \draw[edge] (c1) -- node[above, font=\scriptsize] {$e_2$} (c2);
  \node[right=0.3cm of c2, font=\small, red!70!black]
    {$\neg\varphi$ \;(bug)};
\end{tikzpicture}
\caption{Bounded symbolic execution of computation graphs.
  \textbf{Top:} forward propagation verifies all paths through
  the acyclic DAG (exhaustive for feedforward architectures).
  \textbf{Middle:} inductive step (needed only for recurrent
  architectures with cycles).
  \textbf{Bottom:} when verification fails, a concrete
  counterexample trace identifies the bug location.}
\label{fig:kinduction}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Counterexample Traces}

When the base case fails---Z3 finds a satisfying assignment to
$\neg\varphi(\sigma_i)$ for some $i \leq k$---\textsc{LiquidPy}
extracts a \emph{counterexample trace}: a concrete sequence of
states and transitions leading to the violation.
The trace includes:
\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=2em]
  \item The \textbf{input shape} that triggers the bug.
  \item The \textbf{sequence of layer applications} from input to
    the failing edge.
  \item The \textbf{shape, device, and phase} at each intermediate
    node.
  \item The \textbf{specific constraint violated} (e.g.,
    ``\texttt{fc2} expects in\_features$=$50 but input last dim
    is 20'').
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Safety Certificates}

When both $\mathit{Base}(k)$ and $\mathit{Step}(k)$ are verified,
\textsc{LiquidPy} produces a \emph{safety certificate}: a Z3 proof
object witnessing that all reachable states satisfy $\varphi$.
The certificate is parameterized by symbolic input dimensions
(e.g., batch size, sequence length), meaning it holds for
\emph{all} valid input shapes, not just specific concrete values.

%% ============================================================
\section{Quality-Filtered Contract Discovery}\label{sec:cegar}

Many \texttt{nn.Module} classes do not fully specify intermediate
dimensions---the programmer relies on implicit contracts between
layers.  For example:

\begin{lstlisting}[style=noline]
class AutoEncoder(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, input_dim):
        super().__init__()
        self.encoder = nn.Linear(input_dim, 64)
        self.decoder = nn.Linear(64, input_dim)
    def forward(self, x):
        z = F.relu(self.encoder(x))
        return self.decoder(z)
\end{lstlisting}

The contract ``encoder output dim = decoder input dim = 64'' is
implicit.  \textsc{LiquidPy} discovers it via a counterexample-guided
contract discovery loop, a simplified variant of
CEGAR~\cite{clarke03}.  Unlike general CEGAR, where the abstraction
refinement may require sophisticated predicate synthesis, our
refinement step is deterministic: it reads layer parameters from
the computation graph and propagates dimension constraints backwards
from the failing edge.  This makes the loop a form of
counterexample-guided constraint propagation rather than full
abstraction refinement in the sense of Clarke et al.

\subsection{The Refinement Loop}

\begin{algorithm}[t]
\caption{Counterexample-guided shape contract discovery.}
\label{alg:cegar}
\begin{algorithmic}[1]
\Require Computation graph $G$, safety property $\varphi$,
  max iterations $N$
\Ensure SAFE with contracts, or UNSAFE with counterexample
\State $\mathcal{P} \gets \emptyset$
  \Comment{discovered predicates}
\For{$i = 1, \ldots, N$}
  \State $\psi \gets \varphi \wedge \bigwedge_{p \in \mathcal{P}} p$
  \State result $\gets$ \Call{Verify}{$G, \psi$}
  \If{result = SAFE}
    \State \Return SAFE, $\mathcal{P}$
  \EndIf
  \State cex $\gets$ result.counterexample
  \If{\Call{IsFeasible}{cex}}
    \State \Return UNSAFE, cex
  \EndIf
  \State $p_{\mathit{new}} \gets$
    \Call{SynthesizePredicate}{cex, $G$}
  \If{$\Call{QualityScore}{p_{\mathit{new}}} \geq q_{\min}$}
    \State $\mathcal{P} \gets \mathcal{P} \cup \{p_{\mathit{new}}\}$
  \EndIf
\EndFor
\State \Return UNKNOWN
\end{algorithmic}
\end{algorithm}

The loop (Algorithm~\ref{alg:cegar}) alternates between constraint-based
verification and predicate synthesis.  Unlike Houdini-style
predicate elimination~\cite{flanagan01}, which starts with a large
candidate set and removes predicates that are not inductive, our
loop \emph{accumulates} predicates monotonically: predicates are
only added, never removed, and each candidate is scored for quality
before acceptance.  This ensures that each refinement
iteration strictly increases precision without over-constraining
the valid input space.  The key mechanisms are:

\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=2em]
  \item \textbf{Counterexample trace-back:} When verification returns a
    counterexample, \textsc{LiquidPy} traces the failing assignment
    backwards through the computation graph to identify the
    earliest edge where a shape mismatch originates.
  \item \textbf{Unsat-core-based predicate discovery:} From the
    traced counterexample, \textsc{LiquidPy} queries Z3 for an
    unsat core of the negated safety property under the current
    constraints, yielding a minimal set of dimension equalities
    that must hold.
  \item \textbf{Quality-filtered acceptance:} Each candidate predicate
    is scored by an information-theoretic quality function
    $q(p) = g(p)^{0.3} \cdot c(p)^{0.4} \cdot k(p)^{0.3}$
    evaluating generality, coverage preservation, and consistency
    with known real bugs.  Predicates below threshold $q_{\min}$
    are rejected.
  \item \textbf{Z3-checked feasibility:} Accepted predicates are
    checked for consistency with all previously accumulated
    predicates via a Z3 satisfiability query, ensuring that the
    refined predicate set remains satisfiable.
  \item \textbf{Counterexample feasibility checking:} The loop
    validates that Z3-generated counterexample dimension assignments
    represent physically realizable tensor configurations before
    classifying them as spurious, preventing refinement on
    infeasible counterexamples.
  \item \textbf{Monotonic precision:} Since predicates are only
    added and never removed, the set of admitted behaviors shrinks
    monotonically, guaranteeing convergence.
\end{enumerate}

\paragraph{Step 1: Verify.}
Run verification on the computation graph with the current predicate set.
If safe, return with discovered contracts.

\paragraph{Step 2: Check feasibility.}
When verification returns a counterexample, check whether it corresponds
to a \emph{real} execution path (the counterexample is feasible)
or is an artifact of missing predicates (the counterexample is
spurious).  Feasibility is checked by concretizing symbolic
dimensions and evaluating the path via Z3 satisfiability
checking of the accumulated predicates.

\paragraph{Step 3: Synthesize predicate.}
From a spurious counterexample, extract a new shape predicate that
eliminates it.  The counterexample is traced back through the
computation graph to identify the originating edge, and the
synthesis uses three strategies:
\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=2em]
  \item \textbf{Equality extraction:} If the counterexample
    violates $\mathit{get}(s, i) = c$ at some edge, add the
    predicate $\mathit{last\_dim}(\sigma_j) = c$.
  \item \textbf{Dimension propagation:} If consecutive layers
    have matching in/out dimensions, add
    $\mathit{out\_dim}(\ell_j) = \mathit{in\_dim}(\ell_{j+1})$.
  \item \textbf{Guard extraction:} If the \texttt{forward} method
    contains a shape guard (\texttt{assert x.shape[1] == 64}),
    add the corresponding predicate.
\end{enumerate}
New predicates are checked for consistency with $\mathcal{P}$
via a Z3 satisfiability query before being added to the set.

\subsection{Convergence and Quality Filtering}

\begin{proposition}[Contract Discovery Termination]
The contract discovery loop terminates in at most $|E|$ iterations, where $|E|$
is the number of edges in the computation graph.
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}
Each iteration either returns SAFE/UNSAFE or adds a predicate that
eliminates at least one spurious counterexample.  The number of
distinct spurious counterexamples is bounded by $|E|$ (each edge
can contribute at most one new shape constraint).  Since predicates
are never removed, the loop terminates.
\end{proof}

\paragraph{Predicate quality filtering.}
Unfiltered counterexample-guided refinement can degrade precision at scale:
predicates derived from individual counterexamples may over-constrain
the valid input space, masking real bugs.  We address this with an
information-theoretic predicate quality scorer that evaluates each
candidate predicate along three axes before acceptance:

\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=2em]
  \item \textbf{Generality}: Structural predicates (dimension matching,
    divisibility) score higher than concrete equalities.  A predicate
    $x.\mathsf{shape}[-1] = w.\mathsf{shape}[0]$ preserves more of
    the valid input space than $x.\mathsf{shape}[-1] = 768$.

  \item \textbf{Coverage preservation}: The fraction of the bounded
    input domain $[1, 2048]^d$ that survives after adding the predicate.
    Predicates eliminating $>90\%$ of the space are flagged as likely
    masking real bugs.

  \item \textbf{Consistency}: Whether the predicate conflicts with any
    previously discovered real bugs.  A predicate constraining dimension
    $d$ to value $v$ is rejected if a known-real bug depends on~$d$.
\end{enumerate}

The overall quality score is a weighted geometric mean
$q(p) = g(p)^{0.3} \cdot c(p)^{0.4} \cdot k(p)^{0.3}$
where $g$, $c$, $k$ are the generality, coverage, and consistency scores
respectively.  Predicates with $q(p) < 0.25$ are rejected.

In practice, convergence is fast: across 8 benchmarks,
the loop discovers 8 predicates in an average of 1.75 iterations
with 100\% accuracy.  Quality filtering prevents the F1 degradation
observed in unfiltered loops at scale (see \S\ref{sec:ablation}).

%% ============================================================
\section{Evaluation}\label{sec:eval}

We evaluate \textsc{LiquidPy} on four complementary benchmarks
totaling 47 programs.  All experiments used a single machine with
an Apple M-series processor.

\subsection{PyTea Comparison}\label{sec:pytea-comp}

We compare against PyTea~\cite{pytea} on 27 benchmarks drawn from
PyTea's evaluation categories (matmul, linear, conv, reshape,
broadcast, cat, sequential).  For each benchmark,
ground truth is established by manual inspection.

