\subsection{Baseline Comparison}\label{sec:baseline}

To contextualize \textsc{LiquidPy}'s contribution, we compare against
three baselines on 12 benchmark \texttt{nn.Module} architectures
(7 buggy, 5 correct): (1) a syntactic pattern-matching baseline
that walks the AST to check dimension compatibility without Z3,
(2) GPT-4.1-nano prompted to find shape bugs, and (3) Pyright~1.x /
MyPy~1.x which verify surface-level types only.

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\caption{Shape bug detection on 12 benchmark \texttt{nn.Module} architectures
  (7 buggy, 5 correct).  Bootstrap 95\% CIs on F1.}
\label{tab:baseline}
\begin{tabular}{lccccccl}
\toprule
\textbf{Tool} & \textbf{TP} & \textbf{FP} & \textbf{TN} & \textbf{FN}
  & \textbf{P} & \textbf{R} & \textbf{F1 [95\% CI]} \\
\midrule
Syntactic baseline  & 7 & 0 & 5 & 0 & 1.00 & 1.00 & 1.00 [1.00, 1.00] \\
\textsc{LiquidPy}   & 7 & 0 & 5 & 0 & 1.00 & 1.00 & 1.00 [1.00, 1.00] \\
GPT-4.1-nano        & 7 & 2 & 3 & 0 & 0.778 & 1.00 & 0.875 [0.63, 1.00] \\
Pyright / MyPy      & 0 & 0 & 5 & 7 & ---   & 0.00 & 0.00 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\paragraph{Analysis.}
The syntactic baseline and \textsc{LiquidPy} both achieve perfect F1 on
these 12 benchmarks because the shape mismatches are straightforward
dimension mismatches (e.g., \texttt{Linear(768, 256)} followed by
\texttt{Linear(128, 10)}) detectable via AST pattern matching alone.
GPT-4.1-nano achieves good recall but produces 2 false positives
on correct architectures.  Pyright and MyPy detect no shape bugs,
as expected for tools not designed for shape verification.

\paragraph{Where LiquidPy adds value over syntactic analysis.}
The syntactic baseline cannot handle: (1)~symbolic dimensions
(it only works with concrete values), (2)~broadcasting
compatibility (it cannot determine if two shapes are
broadcast-compatible), (3)~cross-domain bugs (device mismatches,
phase-dependent behavior), or (4)~implicit shape contracts
(discovered via the contract discovery loop).  Our cross-domain evaluation
(\S\ref{sec:cross-domain}) shows that 19 of 24 cross-domain bugs
are structurally uncatchable by any shape-only baseline.
The contract discovery evaluation (\S\ref{sec:cegar-eval}) shows
that \textsc{LiquidPy} discovers implicit contracts not present
in the source code.

