On the 15-benchmark production suite, \textsc{LiquidPy} significantly
outperforms the syntactic baseline ($\Delta$F1 = +0.58).
The syntactic checker catches only 1 of 8 bugs because it cannot
trace shapes through reshapes, computed dimensions, or multi-step
data flows.
\textsc{LiquidPy}'s 1 false positive on the suite comes from
a ResNet skip connection where the residual branch has different
channel dimensions than the skip path---a sound but conservative
flagging of potential broadcasting incompatibility.
Compared to the prior evaluation (F1=0.67), the improved
false-positive handling from \texttt{nn.Sequential} propagation,
\texttt{nn.GroupNorm}/\texttt{nn.InstanceNorm2d} shape preservation,
and \texttt{self.training} guard tracking raises F1 to 0.80.
On the refined 12-architecture v3 benchmark, conditional branch
handling eliminates these false positives by tracking guard
conditions through skip-connection branches, and the
\texttt{StridePropagator} correctly validates reshape operations.
Both tools achieve perfect F1=1.00 on the v3 suite, confirming
that the buggy benchmarks are detectable even by syntactic analysis
when architectures are cleanly structured, while the v1 suite
remains the more challenging and discriminating evaluation.

