%% ============================================================
\section{Related Work}\label{sec:related}

\paragraph{Tensor shape analysis.}
PyTea~\cite{pytea} (ECOOP 2022) is the closest related work,
performing static tensor shape analysis for PyTorch via abstract
interpretation with a constraint-based approach.  PyTea reasons
about individual operations and simple sequential compositions,
but does not model-check entire architectures, track devices, or
handle phase-dependent behavior.  \textsc{LiquidPy} extends the
scope from individual operations to full \texttt{nn.Module}
computation graphs.
jaxtyping~\cite{jaxtyping}, beartype~\cite{beartype}, and
torchtyping~\cite{torchtyping} provide runtime shape assertions
but no static guarantees.  TorchScript~\cite{torchscript} compiles
a Python subset to a typed IR without shape-level verification.

\paragraph{Liquid types and refinement types.}
Liquid types~\cite{rondon08} (PLDI 2008) introduced the framework
of attaching SMT-checkable refinement predicates to types.
Liquid Haskell~\cite{vazou14} brought this to practice.
RefinedC~\cite{sammler21} targets C; Stainless~\cite{hamza19}
targets Scala.  \textsc{LiquidPy} uses the liquid type framework
for shape refinement predicates but contributes the computation
graph model checking layer that is absent from prior refinement
type systems.

\paragraph{Bounded model checking and $k$-induction.}
BMC was introduced by Biere et al.~\cite{biere99} for hardware
verification.  $k$-Induction~\cite{sheeran00} strengthens BMC
with an inductive step.  CBMC~\cite{cbmc} applies BMC to C
programs.  \textsc{LiquidPy} applies bounded symbolic execution
to neural network computation graphs, a novel application domain.
For the acyclic DAGs that arise from feedforward architectures,
forward symbolic propagation is exhaustive and no inductive
argument is needed.

\paragraph{Counterexample-guided refinement.}
Counterexample-guided abstraction refinement~\cite{clarke03}
(CAV 2003) is a standard technique in model checking.
\textsc{LiquidPy}'s contract discovery loop is inspired by CEGAR
but is substantially simpler: the abstraction refinement is
deterministic (reading layer parameters and propagating dimension
constraints backwards), rather than requiring general predicate
synthesis.  We therefore describe it as counterexample-guided
shape contract discovery rather than full CEGAR.

\paragraph{Domain-specific SMT theories.}
Custom theory plugins via Z3's \texttt{UserPropagator}
API~\cite{z3userprop} enable domain-specific decision procedures
to participate in the DPLL(T) loop.  Prior applications include
string solving and regular expression matching.
\textsc{LiquidPy} contributes the first domain-specific theory
for tensor broadcasting semantics, axiomatizing NumPy/PyTorch
broadcasting rules as a first-class Z3 theory with eager
propagation and conflict clause generation.

\paragraph{ML-specific verification.}
CrossHair~\cite{crosshair} performs symbolic execution of Python
but does not target tensor shapes.
TensorFuzz~\cite{tensorfuzz} applies fuzz testing to neural
networks but targets semantic correctness, not shape safety.
DeepLocalize~\cite{deeplocalize} localizes faults via dynamic
analysis.  None of these tools performs static verification of
entire \texttt{nn.Module} architectures.

%% ============================================================
\section{Conclusion}\label{sec:conclusion}

We have presented \textsc{LiquidPy}, the first constraint-based
verifier for neural network computation graphs.  By extracting
data-flow computation graphs from \texttt{nn.Module} classes
and verifying safety properties via forward symbolic constraint
propagation with Z3 over a fully Z3-backed product theory
($\mathcal{T}_{\mathit{shape}} \times \mathcal{T}_{\mathit{device}}
\times \mathcal{T}_{\mathit{phase}}$) using enumeration sorts
for device consistency and phase correctness, together with a
custom \texttt{UserPropagator}-based broadcast theory for
first-class broadcasting reasoning,
\textsc{LiquidPy} catches architecture-level bugs---shape
mismatches, device inconsistencies, and phase-dependent
errors---that no existing tool detects.

On 27 benchmarks shared with PyTea's evaluation, \textsc{LiquidPy}
achieves 85.2\% accuracy versus PyTea's 77.8\% and handles 10
cases beyond PyTea's scope.  On 18 real architectures,
verification accuracy is 94.4\% (17/18 models).
On 18 theory-exercising benchmarks requiring Z3 reasoning about
broadcasting and multi-step shape flows, \textsc{LiquidPy}
achieves F1=1.00 while a syntactic baseline achieves F1=0.00.
On 15 production-style architectures, \textsc{LiquidPy} achieves
F1=0.80 versus F1=0.22 for syntactic analysis; with conditional
branch handling and stride theory, both false positives and false
negatives are eliminated on a refined 12-architecture benchmark,
achieving F1=1.00.
The counterexample-guided contract discovery loop achieves
100\% accuracy across 8 benchmarks.
The cross-domain evaluation demonstrates that 19 of 24
cross-domain bugs are structurally uncatchable by any
shape-only tool.
Path-sensitive guard analysis reduces false positives from
path-insensitive branches.

\paragraph{Limitations.}
The current AST-based layer extraction cannot resolve constructor
parameters defined as variables (e.g., \texttt{nn.Linear(dim, 4*dim)})
in all cases.
Skip connections with channel-dimension changes produce
conservative false positives.
Recurrent architectures (RNNs, LSTMs) are verified only up to a
bounded unrolling depth.

\paragraph{Future work.}
The combined analysis design is extensible: future work includes
adding a dtype theory $\mathcal{T}_{\mathit{dtype}}$ (tracking
float16 overflow, integer truncation), a gradient flow theory
$\mathcal{T}_{\mathit{grad}}$ (detecting detached intermediates,
missing \texttt{zero\_grad}), and interprocedural analysis for
constructor parameter resolution.
Scaling to larger models (100+ layers) will require incremental
verification and compositional reasoning across module boundaries.

%% ============================================================

\appendix

\section{Decidability Proof for $\mathcal{T}_\Pi$}
\label{app:decidability}

We provide the full proof of Theorem~\ref{thm:decidable}.

\begin{proof}
We show that the combination is decidable using the
Tinelli--Zarba extension~\cite{tinelli03} of the Nelson--Oppen
framework, which handles theories with finite sorts.
The classical Nelson--Oppen combination theorem~\cite{nelsonoppen}
requires all component theories to be stably infinite.
Since $\mathcal{T}_{\mathit{device}}$ and
$\mathcal{T}_{\mathit{phase}}$ have finite sorts, the classical
theorem does not directly apply.  The Tinelli--Zarba extension
handles this case by enumerating arrangements over the finite sorts.

We verify the premises for each component theory.

\paragraph{1. Decidability and sort structure.}

\emph{$\mathcal{T}_{\mathit{shape}}$:}
The sort $\mathit{Shape}$ is interpreted as finite tuples over
$\mathbb{Z}_{\geq 1}$.  For any satisfiable QF formula $\phi$,
we can extend any model with arbitrarily many fresh shape tuples
(e.g., tuples of all-1s of increasing length), so the sort has
arbitrarily large models.  Thus $\mathcal{T}_{\mathit{shape}}$ is
stably infinite.

\emph{$\mathcal{T}_{\mathit{device}}$:}
The device sort is finite ($|\mathit{Dev}| = n$ for some fixed
$n$), implemented as a Z3 enumeration sort.  This theory is
\emph{not} stably infinite.
The Tinelli--Zarba extension~\cite{tinelli03} handles finite sorts
by enumerating all possible arrangements (partitions of shared
variables into equivalence classes) over the finite domain.
Since $|\mathit{Dev}|$ is small (typically $\leq 8$), this
enumeration is efficient.  In practice, device checking uses
Z3 equality constraints over enumeration sort constants.

\emph{$\mathcal{T}_{\mathit{phase}}$:}
$|\mathit{Phase}| = 2$, also implemented as a Z3 enumeration sort.
Same finite-sort treatment applies.

\paragraph{2. Signature disjointness.}

$\mathcal{T}_{\mathit{shape}}$ uses functions
$\{\mathit{get}, \mathit{len}, \mathit{set}, \mathit{prod}\}$
over sorts $\{\mathit{Shape}, \mathit{Dim}, \mathit{Idx}\}$.
$\mathcal{T}_{\mathit{device}}$ uses $\{\mathit{dev}\}$ over
$\{\mathit{Dev}, \mathit{Tensor}\}$.
$\mathcal{T}_{\mathit{phase}}$ uses $\{\mathit{phase}\}$ over
$\{\mathit{Phase}, \mathit{Module}\}$.
The only shared sort is $\mathit{Tensor}/\mathit{Module}$
(a tensor belongs to a module).  The cross-sort axioms
(Definition~\ref{def:product}) introduce shared variables but
no shared function symbols.  We handle sharing via explicit
equality propagation in the Nelson--Oppen procedure.

\paragraph{3. Decidability of each component.}

\emph{$\mathcal{T}_{\mathit{shape}}$:}
With concrete tuple lengths, the quantifier-free fragment reduces
to QF-LIA (for matmul, broadcast, cat, linear) or QF-NIA (for
reshape).  QF-LIA is decidable~\cite{presburger29}; QF-NIA is
decidable when the number of variables is bounded (which it is:
at most $2 \times \max(\mathit{ndim})$ variables per constraint).

\emph{$\mathcal{T}_{\mathit{device}}$:}
QF satisfiability of equality constraints over a finite domain is
decidable by enumeration (NP-complete via reduction to graph
coloring, but the domain is small).

\emph{$\mathcal{T}_{\mathit{phase}}$:}
QF satisfiability over a two-element Boolean algebra is trivially
decidable.

\paragraph{4. Combination procedure.}

In practice, we rely on Z3's built-in theory combination, which
natively handles the interaction between arithmetic constraints
(for shapes) and finite-domain constraints (for devices and phases).
Conceptually, the procedure follows the Tinelli--Zarba
framework~\cite{tinelli03}:

\begin{enumerate}
  \item Purify the input formula: replace cross-theory terms with
    fresh variables and add defining equalities.
  \item Partition the purified formula into
    $\phi_{\mathit{shape}}$, $\phi_{\mathit{device}}$,
    $\phi_{\mathit{phase}}$.
  \item Propagate equalities between shared variables until
    fixpoint.
  \item Check satisfiability of each component independently.
  \item For the finite sorts ($\mathit{Dev}$, $\mathit{Phase}$),
    enumerate all possible arrangements (partitions of shared
    variables into equivalence classes).
\end{enumerate}

Since each step is decidable and the enumeration is finite, the
overall procedure terminates and is correct (by the
Tinelli--Zarba theorem~\cite{tinelli03}).
\end{proof}

\paragraph{Complexity characterization.}

\begin{proposition}[Combined Complexity]
The QF satisfiability of $\mathcal{T}_\Pi$ is:
\begin{enumerate}
  \item In PTIME when all dimensions are concrete and no reshape
    is used.
  \item In NP when dimensions are concrete and reshape is used
    (QF-NIA with bounded variables).
  \item NP-hard for reshape satisfiability with symbolic
    dimensions.
\end{enumerate}
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}
(1)~Without reshape, all shape constraints are conjunctions of
linear equalities/inequalities over concrete integers, checkable in
$O(d)$ per constraint where $d$ is the maximum number of dimensions.
Device and phase constraints are constant-time (Z3 enumeration sort
equality and two-element enumeration sort, respectively).

(2)~With reshape, the product constraint $\prod s_i = \prod s'_j$
involves multiplication.  With bounded variables (at most $2d$
per constraint), this is in NP.

(3)~By reduction from PARTITION.  Given a multiset
$\{a_1, \ldots, a_n\}$, construct a tensor with $n$ symbolic
dimensions and ask whether the dimensions can be split into two
groups whose products are equal.  This directly encodes the
PARTITION problem: each dimension must be assigned to one of
two reshape targets, and the products must match.  Since
PARTITION is NP-complete, reshape satisfiability is NP-hard.
\end{proof}

%% ============================================================
\section{Shape Algebra}\label{app:shapes}

\subsection{Broadcasting}

NumPy/PyTorch broadcasting aligns shapes from the right.
Given $A$ with shape $(s_1,\ldots,s_m)$ and $B$ with shape
$(t_1,\ldots,t_n)$, broadcasting succeeds iff for each aligned pair
$(s_i,t_j)$: $s_i=t_j$, $s_i=1$, or $t_j=1$.
The Z3 encoding:
\[
  \bigwedge_{k=1}^{\max(m,n)} \left(
    s'_k = t'_k \lor s'_k = 1 \lor t'_k = 1
  \right)
\]
where $s',t'$ are 1-padded to equal length.

\subsection{Matrix Multiplication}

For \texttt{A @ B} with $A : (\ldots,m,k)$, $B : (\ldots,k,n)$:
result $(\ldots,m,n)$; batch dimensions broadcastable; inner
dimensions match: $\mathit{cols}(A)=\mathit{rows}(B)$.

The Z3 encoding:
\begin{lstlisting}[style=noline,language={},basicstyle=\ttfamily\small]
(assert (= (select shapeA (- ndimA 1))
           (select shapeB (- ndimB 2))))
\end{lstlisting}

\subsection{Concatenation}

\texttt{torch.cat([A,B], dim=d)}: all dimensions except $d$ must
match; dimension $d$ of result is $s_A[d]+s_B[d]$.

\subsection{nn.Linear}

\texttt{nn.Linear(in,out)} transforms the last dimension:
$(\ldots,\mathit{in}) \to (\ldots,\mathit{out})$.

\subsection{nn.Conv2d}

\texttt{nn.Conv2d(c\_in, c\_out, kernel\_size)} requires the input
channel dimension $s_x[1] = c\_\mathit{in}$ and produces output with
$c\_\mathit{out}$ channels: $(N, c\_\mathit{out}, H', W')$ where
$H' = \lfloor (H + 2p - k) / s \rfloor + 1$ for padding $p$,
kernel size $k$, stride $s$.

\subsection{Reshape}

\texttt{x.reshape(s)} requires $\prod s_x[i] = \prod s[j]$.
The Z3 encoding uses nonlinear integer arithmetic when dimensions
are symbolic.

