\section{Guard Harvesting}\label{app:guards}

Guard harvesting is a secondary contribution of \textsc{LiquidPy},
providing refinement predicates from syntactic sources.  While the
primary contribution is the constraint-based verifier for computation
graphs, guard harvesting supports the null-safety layer of the
analysis.

\textsc{LiquidPy} harvests qualifier predicates from seven syntactic
sources:

\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=2em]
  \item \textbf{Conditional guards:} \texttt{if x is not None},
        \texttt{if isinstance(x, int)}, \texttt{if x > 0}.
  \item \textbf{Early-exit guards:} \texttt{if y == 0: raise}---the
        negation holds on the continuation.
  \item \textbf{Assertions:} \texttt{assert x is not None}.
  \item \textbf{Default values:} \texttt{x = d.get(k, default)}.
  \item \textbf{Exception handlers:} \texttt{except AttributeError}.
  \item \textbf{Walrus operators:} \texttt{if (m := f()) is not None}.
  \item \textbf{Comprehension filters:} \texttt{[x for x in xs if x
        is not None]}.
\end{enumerate}

Guard harvesting from these sources achieves $P{=}1.00$,
$R{=}0.90$, $F_1{=}0.95$ on null-safety benchmarks.

\subsection{Guard Transfer Table}

Table~\ref{tab:transfers} lists all 13 guard patterns recognized by
\textsc{LiquidPy}.

\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{Guard qualifier transfers.  $\Gamma^+$ and $\Gamma^-$
  denote qualifiers along the true and false branches.}
\label{tab:transfers}
\small
\begin{tabular}{@{}lll@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Guard pattern} & $\Gamma^+$ & $\Gamma^-$ \\
\midrule
\texttt{x is None}        & $v = \texttt{None}$ & $v \neq \texttt{None}$ \\
\texttt{x is not None}    & $v \neq \texttt{None}$ & $v = \texttt{None}$ \\
\texttt{isinstance(x,T)}  & $v \neq \texttt{None},\, \mathit{type}(v){=}T$ & $\mathit{type}(v) \neq T$ \\
\texttt{if x:} (truthy)   & $v \neq \texttt{None}$ (if Optional) & --- \\
\texttt{if not x:}        & --- & $v \neq \texttt{None}$ (if Optional) \\
\texttt{x == c}           & $v = c$ & $v \neq c$ \\
\texttt{x != c}           & $v \neq c$ & $v = c$ \\
\texttt{x > c}            & $v > c$ & $v \leq c$ \\
\texttt{x >= c}           & $v \geq c$ & $v < c$ \\
\texttt{x < c}            & $v < c$ & $v \geq c$ \\
\texttt{x <= c}           & $v \leq c$ & $v > c$ \\
\texttt{hasattr(x,a)}     & $\mathit{hasattr}(v,a),\, v \neq \texttt{None}$ & --- \\
\texttt{x in coll}        & $v \in S$ & --- \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\subsection{Typing Rules}

The liquid type foundation uses the judgment
$\Gamma \vdash e : \{v{:}\,T \mid \varphi\}$.
Key rules include guard narrowing:
\[
\frac{
  \Gamma, x{:}\{v{:}\,T \mid \varphi \wedge \llbracket g \rrbracket\}
     \vdash e_1 : \tau_1 \qquad
  \Gamma, x{:}\{v{:}\,T \mid \varphi \wedge \neg\llbracket g \rrbracket\}
     \vdash e_2 : \tau_2
}{
  \Gamma, x{:}\{v{:}\,T \mid \varphi\}
     \vdash \mathtt{if}\;g\;\mathtt{:}\;e_1\;\mathtt{else:}\;e_2
     : \tau_1 \sqcup \tau_2
}
\]

And early-exit guards:
\[
\frac{
  e_1 = \mathtt{raise}\;\_ \text{ or } e_1 = \mathtt{return}\;\_ \qquad
  \Gamma, x{:}\{v{:}\,T \mid \varphi \wedge \neg\llbracket g \rrbracket\}
     \vdash e_2 : \tau
}{
  \Gamma, x{:}\{v{:}\,T \mid \varphi\}
     \vdash \mathtt{if}\;g\;\mathtt{:}\;e_1\;\mathtt{else:}\;e_2 : \tau
}
\]

