\section{Contract Discovery Algorithm Pseudocode}\label{app:cegar}

Algorithm~\ref{alg:cegar} in the main text provides the high-level
structure.  Here we detail the predicate synthesis subroutine.

\begin{algorithm}[H]
\caption{\textsc{SynthesizePredicate}: extract a shape predicate
  from a spurious counterexample.}
\label{alg:synth}
\begin{algorithmic}[1]
\Require Counterexample cex, computation graph $G$
\Ensure New predicate $p$
\State edge $\gets$ cex.failing\_edge
\State $\ell \gets \lambda(\text{edge})$
  \Comment{layer at failing edge}
\State $s_{\mathit{in}} \gets$ cex.source\_state.shape
\State $s_{\mathit{out}} \gets \tau_\ell(s_{\mathit{in}})$
  \Comment{expected output shape}
\If{edge.target has successor edge $e'$}
  \State $\ell' \gets \lambda(e')$
  \State $c \gets \mathit{in\_dim}(\ell')$
    \Comment{required input dim}
  \State \Return
    $\mathit{last\_dim}(s_{\mathit{out}}) = c$
\Else
  \State \Return
    $\mathit{shape}(\text{edge.target}) = s_{\mathit{out}}$
\EndIf
\end{algorithmic}
\end{algorithm}

The key insight is that spurious counterexamples in computation
graphs have a specific structure: they arise at edges where the
shape transfer function of one layer produces a shape incompatible
with the next layer's precondition.  The synthesized predicate
directly encodes the missing compatibility constraint.

